default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultJapanese Knotweeddefault: What is the extent of the problem?default1.1
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultJapanese Knotweed can cause physical damage to buildings as it has the potential to infiltrate through cracks and gaps in concrete and tarmac, expanding with enough force to cause serious structural damage.  It can damage underground sewers, block drains and there have even been incidents of Japanese Knotweed growing within cavity walls.  
default1.2
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultIn 2010, it was estimated that the 
defaultannualdefault cost of dealing with Japanese Knotweed in Britain was in the region of £165million. 
default 
defaultTo give a recent high-profile example
default, at the Olympic site in East London, the Royal Horticultural Society estimated that the cost of removing and disposing of Japanese Knotweed was £70million.
default2
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe cdefaulturrent law in the UKdefault2.1
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultSection 14(2) of the Wildlife and Countryside Act 1981 states that “if any person plants or otherwise causes to grow in the wild any plant which is included in Part II of Schedule 9, he shall be guilty of an offence”. Japanese Knotweed is contained in Part II of Schedule 9, however, ra
defaultther unhelpfully, the Act does not 
defaultdefine the term “in the wild”. DEFRA
default has published guidance on the matter
default stating that
default “the wild” can “be broadly described as the general countryside/open environment”.  
defaultThe guidance 
defaultwould seem to exclude domestic gardens, but 
defaultdoes not clarify whether, for example, 
defaulta company’s car park, a railway embankment or a verge on a public highway 
defaultwould
default fall into the d
defaultefinition of “open environment”. 
default2.2
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultUnder the Environmental Protection Act 1990, Japanese Knotweed (and soil contaminated with rhizomes), is considered to be a “controlled waste” and is subject to more stringent controls. However, Japanese Knotweed is
default not
default a “
defaultnotifiable
default” weed under the Weeds Act 1959, which means that notices cannot be served by local authorities requiring that land owners prevent its spread.
default2.3
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultIn addition to the legislation mentioned above, it is also possible for a landowner to bring a common law (private) nuisance claim against a neighbouring landowner where Japanese Knotweed is encroaching over the property boundary.  However, 
defaultif Japanese Knotweed is present on adjacent land but has not crossed the property boundary, it will be very difficult to bring a claim for nuisance
default.
